\chapter{1899 Provisional}
\begin{marginfigure}
\includegraphics[width=1.0\textwidth]{../british-guiana/14019_1351_1.jpg}
\caption{Auction: 14019 - The "Foxley" Collections of British Guiana and British Honduras 
Lot: 1351 British Guiana
1899 (June - Feb.) Two Cents Surcharges
2c. on 5c. showing variety "cints", fine used. S.G. 222c, unpriced. 
Estimate £60 to £80.}
\end{marginfigure}

ON the 1st January, 1899, Imperial Penny Postage came into operation. There was an
increased demand for 2c. stamps, and a diminished use for 5c. and multiples thereof.
The higher values of the Jubilee stamps issued six months previously had not been largely
purchased. There was little demand for the two new values 10c. and 15c. introduced into
this issue and the Commissioners, faced with a large stock of these stamps, which had been
costly to produce, pointed out to the Government that there was in stock 96,600 at l0c.
and 124,680 at 15c., and on the 8th February, asked for instructions as to overprinting
them with a 2c. value. The Governor approved and the stamps were overprinted at the
\textit{Daily Chronicle} printing office and issued on the 22nd February.



There was a big demand for these provisional stamps and the Commissioners suggested
that they should not be sold at one time, but that supplies should be obtained at intervals of three days.

