\end{marginfigure}
Later the Postmaster General intimated to the Government (on 28th February) that
he had in stock at the Post Office: 39,656 of l0c. and 12,345 of 15c. stamps, which were
issued to him previous to the overprinting and suggested that of these numbers there should be overprinted "Two Cents"—30,000 of l0c. and 10,000 of 15c., the remainder, 9,656
of l0c. and 2,345 of 15c., he thought would be sold at their original value as there was
still a demand for them.

The Governor sanctioned this proposal on the 4th March, but only 30,000 of 10c. and
6,000 of 15c. were overprinted. Further, the Postmaster-General, seeing that the 5c. stamps
were being very slowly absorbed by the public demand, recommended that this value
also, of which there was a stock of 207,900, should be dealt with in a similar manner. The
recommendation was sanctioned, and the remaining stock was overprinted and issued
on the 15th June.
