A number of errors occurred in the printing, by carelessness or design. One of the first
discovered at the Post Office was the GENTS error in the sheet of 1Oc., which caused a
great amount of trouble to the Post Office. Quantities of sheets were purchased at the
Post Office, the error removed from each sheet, and the balance deposited in the Post
Office Savings Bank as a cash deposit. At that time it was permitted by the regulations
to make deposits by means of postage stamps. The Stamp Commissioner wrote on the
24th February: "Can anything be done to remedy this? Shall we take out the one stamp
and destroy it, or can we refuse to take overprinted Jubilee stamps on deposit?

The Government could not at that time take steps to cancel the system of making deposits
by means of postage stamps, but the cancelment took place on the 24th April, 1901.
A sheet of the 10c. with inverted overprint, and a sheet of the 15c. doubly overprinted
were discovered. These errors were brought into great publicity through the publication in
the Philatelic Press of letters to firms of Stamp Merchants, which purported to come
from a Postal Official, offering these errors at high prices. 

\begin{marginfigure}
\includegraphics[width=1.0\textwidth]{../british-guiana/14019_1353_1.jpg}
